| 2018\n| [[2018 Macau Masters|Macau Masters]]\n| {{flagicon|WAL}} [[Ryan Day (snooker player)|Ryan Day]]<br />{{flagicon|CHN}} [[Zhao Xintong]]<br />{{flagicon|CHN}} [[Zhou Yuelong]]\n| {{flagicon|WAL}} [[Mark Williams (snooker player)|Mark Williams]]<br />{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Joe Perry (snooker player)|Joe Perry]]<br />{{flagicon|HKG}} [[Marco Fu]]<br />{{flagicon|CHN}} [[Zhang Anda]]\n| align=\"center\" | 5\u20131\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Barry Hawkins}}\n*{{Official website|1=http://onqpromotions.co.uk/players/BarryHawkins.html}}\n*[http://www.worldsnooker.com/players/barry-hawkins/ Barry Hawkins] at ''worldsnooker.com''\n*\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090913063729/http://www.global-snooker.com/Barry-Hawkins.asp Profile at Global Snooker]\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hawkins, Barry}}\n[[Category:English snooker players]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Dartford]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English professional snooker player}}\n{{EngvarB|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox snooker player\n| name          = Barry Hawkins\n| image         = Barry Hawkins at Snooker German Masters (Martin Rulsch) 2014-01-29 03.jpg\n| caption       = German Masters 2014\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1979|04|23|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[Ditton, Kent]], [[England]]\n| Sport country = {{ENG}}\n| Nickname      = The Hawk\n| Professional  = 1996/1997, 2000\u2013\n| High ranking  = 4 {{smaller|(March\u2013May, June\u2013July 2014)}} \n| Prize money   = [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]2,440,022\n| High break    = '''[[Maximum break|147]]''' {{smaller|(3 times)}} \n| Century break = 339\n| Ranking wins  = 3\n| Minor wins    = 1\n| Other wins    = 5\n| World champ   = \n}}\n\n'''Barry Hawkins''' (born 23 April 1979) is an English professional [[snooker]] player from [[Ditton, Kent|Ditton]] in Kent. He turned professional in 1996, but only rose to prominence in the [[Snooker season 2004/2005|2004/2005 snooker season]], when he reached the last 16 of the [[2004 UK Championship (snooker)|2004 UK Championship]], the quarter-finals of the [[2004 British Open (snooker)|2004 British Open]], and the semi-finals of the [[2005 Welsh Open (snooker)|2005 Welsh Open]]. He has now spent twelve successive seasons ranked inside the top 32. He reached his first ranking final and won his first ranking title at the [[2012 Australian Goldfields Open]].\n\nHawkins has played in the televised stages of every World Championship since he made his Crucible Theatre debut in [[2006 World Snooker Championship|2006]]. He lost in the first round on his first five appearances, but reached the second round in [[2011 World Snooker Championship|2011]] and [[2012 World Snooker Championship|2012]]. Rated an 80\u20131 outsider for the [[2013 World Snooker Championship]] before the tournament began, he surprised many by defeating opponents including world number{{nbsp}}1 [[Mark Selby]] and top Chinese player [[Ding Junhui]] to reach the final, which he lost to defending champion [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]].<ref>{{cite news | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/22421611 | title = Ronnie O'Sullivan beats Barry Hawkins to retain World title | first = Ben |last = Dirs | accessdate = 6 May 2013|date = 6 May 2013 |work = BBC Sport }}</ref> Hawkins has since reached the semi-finals of the World Championship in 2014, 2015, 2017 and 2018, and reached the final of the [[2016 Masters (snooker)|Masters]] in 2016.\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early career===\n{{expand section|date=May 2013}}\n\nBefore taking up snooker professionally he was an office clerk.<ref name=\"hawk\">[http://www.worldsnooker.com/player_list-8265.htm World Snooker: Barry Hawkins] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091013172041/http://www.worldsnooker.com/player_list-8265.htm |date=13 October 2009 }}- Official World Snooker profile.</ref> He reached the Top 32 in [[Snooker world rankings 2004/2005|the rankings in 2004/2005]], having reached the semi-finals of 2005's [[Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]], as well as the last sixteen of three other tournaments.\n\n===2005/2006===\n[[Snooker season 2005/2006|In 2005/2006]], he reached the semi-finals of the [[Grand Prix (snooker)|Grand Prix]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.snooker.org/trn/0506/gp2005_res.shtml |title=WWW Snooker: Grand Prix 2005 |publisher=Snooker.org |accessdate=2013-05-06}}</ref> and the Welsh Open again, and also beat the high-ranked [[Ding Junhui]] to qualify for the [[World Snooker Championship|World Championship]] for the first time.<ref>[http://superengland.com/sport/content/view/287/38/ Article on Super England] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080513062344/http://superengland.com/sport/content/view/287/38/ |date=13 May 2008 }}</ref> This cemented Hawkins' place in the Top 16 of the [[Snooker world rankings 2006/2007|rankings for the 2006/2007 season]].\n\nAt the World Championship in [[Sheffield]], however, Hawkins faced former Champion [[Ken Doherty]] in the first round, and in the intimidating [[Crucible Theatre]] lost 10\u20131. He told the [[BBC]] that \"I just couldn't perform and I don't know why{{nbsp}}... I'm gutted after such a good season to have performed like that.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.betfinder.co.uk/articles/world-snooker-2007-players.asp |title=888.com World Snooker Championship Player Guide & Wallchart (search for Barry Hawkins) |publisher=Bet Finder |date=14 January 2007 |accessdate=2013-05-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130625030353/http://www.betfinder.co.uk/articles/world-snooker-2007-players.asp |archivedate=25 June 2013 |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\n===2006\u20132009===\nThe 2006/2007 season saw Hawkins disappointed following two strong seasons. He reached the final of the non-ranking Kilkenny Irish Masters,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/sport/snooker/tm_headline=rocket-cruises-in-as-hawkins-wilts&method=full&objectid=18740533&siteid=89520-name_page.html |title=The Mirrow: Rocket cruises in as Hawkins wilts |work=Daily Mirror |date=12 March 2007 |accessdate=2013-05-06}}</ref> however his only run past the last 16 in a ranking event was at the [[China Open (snooker)|China Open]], when he reached the semi-finals, again beating Ding along the way. He had one foot in his first final against [[Jamie Cope]] in the semi final, but Cope was able to obtain the snookers he needed to stay in the match and went on to win 6\u20135.\nA first-round defeat by [[Fergal O'Brien]] at the World Championship<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/6581657.stm |title=BBC Sport: O'Brien stumbles to Hawkins win |work=BBC News |date=23 April 2007 |accessdate=2013-05-06}}</ref> cost him his Top 16 place, and left him outside the Top 32 on the [[Snooker world rankings|single-year rankings]].\n\nEarly in the 2007/2008 season, Hawkins won the [[Masters Qualifying Event|qualifying tournament]] for the [[2008 Masters (snooker)|2008 SAGA Insurance Masters]], beating [[Kurt Maflin]]. He won five other matches, also beating top-32 players [[Nigel Bond]] and [[Jamie Cope]]. He also reached the last 16 at the [[Grand Prix 2007 (snooker)|Grand Prix]], [[2007 UK Snooker Championship|UK Championship]] and [[China Open 2008 (snooker)|China Open]].\n\nHe started the [[Snooker season 2008/2009|2008/2009 season]] with a quarter-final appearance at the [[2008 Northern Ireland Trophy]], by beating [[Jimmy White]] 5\u20133, [[Marco Fu]] 5\u20132 and [[Ryan Day (snooker player)|Ryan Day]] 5\u20133 where he played [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]], losing 5\u20134 after producing a brave fightback from 4\u20131 to level at 4\u20134. He then won at least his opening match in the next four ranking events, reaching the provisional top 16. He did not qualify for the events in Wales and China, but made it to the World Championship by beating [[Daniel Wells (snooker player)|Daniel Wells]] 10\u20139,<ref name=\"Legend Davis through to Crucible\">[http://www.worldsnooker.com/ws_championship_qualifiers_second_news-24360.htm?tid=122 Legend Davis through to Crucible]</ref> but lost in the first round, finishing one place short of a return to the top 16.\n\nFrom 2006\u20132010, Hawkins's record at the World Championship was unsuccessful, with a win\u2013loss record of 0\u20135. As well as the aforementioned one-sided defeat by Doherty, Hawkins narrowly lost in the first round the following two years as well, to [[Fergal O'Brien]] and [[Ali Carter]] respectively. Coincidentally, on both occasions Hawkins lost by very close 10\u20139 defeats, having recovered from 9\u20136 behind each time. In 2009 Hawkins missed out on a chance to take his match with former champion [[Graeme Dott]] to a deciding frame, and lost 10\u20138. The following year, Hawkins led defending champion [[John Higgins (snooker player)|John Higgins]] 5\u20133 before Higgins won seven of the next eight frames to progress.\n\n===2010/2011===\nHawkins played well at the [[2010 World Open (snooker)|World Open]] (formerly the Grand Prix) in defeating [[Mark Selby]] (3\u20132) as well as former World Champion [[Ken Doherty]] (3\u20131) before losing 3\u20132 to [[Mark Williams (snooker player)|Mark Williams]].\n\nHawkins qualified for the [[2011 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]] for the sixth year running, where he was drawn against [[Stephen Maguire]] in the first round. Having never won a match at the Crucible before, Hawkins led Maguire 4\u20130, 5\u20131, 6\u20132 and 8\u20134 before seeing Maguire level the match at 8\u20138 and then 9\u20139. However, Hawkins held his nerve in the deciding frame to finally end his losing run at the World Championship.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/snooker/13127971.stm|title=Barry Hawkins delight at Crucible win|date=19 April 2011|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=2011-04-21| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110422071344/http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/snooker/13127971.stm| archivedate= 22 April 2011 | url-status= live}}</ref> In the second round, Hawkins was defeated 13\u201312 by world No. 11 [[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]].\n\n===2011/2012===\nHawkins reached the [[Players Tour Championship 2011/2012 \u2013 Finals|PTC Finals]] in the [[Snooker season 2011/2012|2011/2012 season]] largely thanks to semi-final runs in [[Players Tour Championship 2011/2012 \u2013 Event 3|Event 3]] and [[Players Tour Championship 2011/2012 \u2013 Event 5|Event 5]]. He finished 22nd on the [[Players Tour Championship 2011/2012#Order of Merit|Order of Merit]], inside the top 24 who qualified.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?template=10&season=2011|title=Order of Merit|publisher=Snooker.org |date=8 January 2012|accessdate=20 May 2012}}</ref> In the Finals he lost in the first round 3\u20134 to [[Jack Lisowski]].<ref name=\"2011/12\">{{cite web | url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=16&season=2011 | title=Barry Hawkins 2011/2012 | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=20 May 2012}}</ref> Hawkins won the non-ranking [[2012 Snooker Shoot-Out|Snooker Shoot-Out]], a tournament where the winner of each round is determined by a single 10-minute frame. He beat [[Graeme Dott]] in the final and picked up a cheque for [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]32,000, the biggest of his career to date.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://eurosport.yahoo.com/29012012/58/hawkins-wins-snooker-shoot.html | archive-url=https://archive.today/20120711130637/http://eurosport.yahoo.com/29012012/58/hawkins-wins-snooker-shoot.html | url-status=dead | archive-date=11 July 2012 | title=Hawkins wins Snooker Shoot-Out | publisher=[[Eurosport]] | date=29 January 2012 | accessdate=20 May 2012 }}</ref>\n\nHawkins' best run in the ranking events came in the final and biggest tournament of the season, the [[2012 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]]. He qualified by beating [[David Morris (snooker player)|David Morris]] and was drawn to play world number one [[Mark Selby]], who had come into the event having suffered a neck injury and declaring himself fit to play only one week before.<ref name=\"2011/12\"/> Hawkins comfortably won 10\u20133 to face [[Matthew Stevens]] in the second round.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.thisislondon.co.uk/sport/other-sports/mark-selby-equals-unwanted-record-7681104.html | title=Mark Selby equals unwanted record | work=[[Evening Standard]] |location=London | date=26 April 2012 | accessdate=20 May 2012}}</ref> He led 8\u20136 after two sessions in a bid to reach his first quarter-final at the [[Crucible Theatre|Crucible]], but had no answer to Stevens in the latter stages as he won seven of the last 10 frames to take the match 13\u201311.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/kentonline/sport/2012/may/1/barry_hawkins.aspx | title=Barry Hawkins is beaten by Matthew Stevens in the second round of the World Snooker Championships at the Crucible | publisher=Kent Online | accessdate=20 May 2012}}</ref> Hawkins finished the season ranked world number 22.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/1d/b0/0,,13165~176157,00.pdf |title=Official World Ranking List for the 2012/2013 Season |accessdate=20 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120522154016/http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/1d/b0/0,,13165~176157,00.pdf |archivedate=22 May 2012 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Barry Hawkins at Snooker German Masters (DerHexer) 2013-01-30 4.jpg|thumb|Hawkins playing at German Masters 2013.]]\n\n===2012/2013===\nHawkins began the [[Snooker season 2012/2013|2012/2013 season]] at the [[2012 Wuxi Classic|Wuxi Classic]], where he faced [[Mark Selby]] in the first round once more, this time losing 2\u20135.<ref name=\"2012/13\">{{cite web | url=http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=16&season=2012 | title=Barry Hawkins 2012/2013 | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=15 July 2012}}</ref>\n\n====First ranking title====\nHis next ranking event was the [[2012 Australian Goldfields Open|Australian Goldfields Open]] in [[Bendigo]], where he defeated [[Xiao Guodong]] (5\u20131), [[Matthew Stevens]] (5\u20132), [[Matthew Selt]] (5\u20133), and [[Mark Davis (snooker player)|Mark Davis]] (6\u20134) to reach the first ranking event final of his 16-year professional career.<ref name=\"2012/13\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=Hawkins Reaches Maiden Final|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~2849554,00.html|work=worldsnooker.com|publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]]|date=14 July 2012|accessdate=15 July 2012}}</ref> He faced [[Peter Ebdon]] and finished the first session of the match leading 5\u20133, which included a spell of four successive frames that meant Ebdon had not potted a ball for over an hour. In the evening session Hawkins won all four frames played to take the title with a 9\u20133 victory.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/18848619 | title= Australian Open 2012: Barry Hawkins defeats Peter Ebdon | date=16 July 2012}}</ref> He made three centuries in the final and climbed to world number 20 thanks to the win, as well as earning praise from Ebdon himself.<ref name=\"Aus\">{{cite web|title=Hawkins on Top Down Under|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~2850028,00.html|work=worldsnooker.com|publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]]|date=15 July 2012|accessdate=15 July 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120718025642/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0%2C%2C13165~2850028%2C00.html|archivedate=18 July 2012|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\n====Other tournaments====\nDespite then losing in the first round of the [[2012 Shanghai Masters|Shanghai Masters]] and in qualifying for the [[2012 International Championship|International Championship]], Hawkins climbed into the top 16 in November meaning he would be in the main draw in the [[2013 Masters (snooker)|Masters]] for the first time since 2007.<ref name=\"2012/13\"/><ref>{{cite web |title=Official world rankings issued after the International Championship 2012 |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/6a/b9/0,,13165~178538,00.pdf |work=worldsnooker.com |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]] |accessdate=6 November 2012 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130616130312/http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/6a/b9/0,,13165~178538,00.pdf |archivedate=16 June 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy }}</ref> [[Neil Robertson (snooker player)|Neil Robertson]] beat him 6\u20132 in the [[2012 UK Championship (snooker)|UK Championship]] and in the Masters he was 5\u20134 up against [[Judd Trump]] but missed two pots when well placed to win the match and instead went to lose 5\u20136, a result which left Hawkins \"devastated\".<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/kent_messenger/sport/2013/january/16/barry_hawkins.aspx | title=Barry Hawkins 'devastated' after loss to Judd Trump at 2013 Masters | publisher=Kent Online | accessdate=24 April 2013}}</ref> He bounced back at the next ranking event, the [[2013 German Masters|German Masters]], by seeing off [[Dechawat Poomjaeng]] 5\u20132, [[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]] 5\u20131 and [[Mark Selby]] 5\u20131 to reach the semi-finals.<ref name=\"2012/13\"/> He lost 4\u20136 to [[Marco Fu]] in a long match which finished after midnight local time and included a bout of safety which lasted almost an hour.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/news/snooker-fu-outlasts-hawkins-set-carter-final-233632629.html | title=Snooker \u2013 Fu outlasts Hawkins to set up Carter final | publisher=[[Eurosport]] | accessdate=24 April 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130204145639/http://uk.eurosport.yahoo.com/news/snooker-fu-outlasts-hawkins-set-carter-final-233632629.html | archivedate=4 February 2013 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Hawkins failed to get past the second round in the [[2013 World Open (snooker)|World Open]], [[2013 China Open (snooker)|China Open]] or [[2013 Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]].<ref name=\"2012/13\"/> He played in eight of the minor-ranking [[Players Tour Championship 2012/2013|Players Tour Championship]] events with his best result being a semi-final defeat by [[Joe Swail]] in the first [[European Tour 2012/2013 \u2013 Event 1|European Tour Event]]. Two further quarter-final defeats saw him finish 15th on the Order of Merit to qualify for the [[Players Tour Championship 2012/2013 \u2013 Finals|Finals]], where he lost 1\u20134 to Robertson in the second round.<ref name=\"2012/13\"/><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?template=10 | title=Order of Merit 2012/2013 | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=24 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n====World Championship final====\nAt the [[2013 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]], he put [[Jack Lisowski]] under sustained pressure with his superior safety game in a 10\u20133 win to face [[Mark Selby]] in the second round.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~3152628,00.html | title=Barry Potter Whacks Jack | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=24 April 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130425053437/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0%2C%2C13165~3152628%2C00.html | archivedate=25 April 2013 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> Hawkins was 7\u20139 behind to the world number one after the second session but came back to triumph 13\u201310 in a win he described as the best of his career.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~3159479,00.html | title=Hawk Ends Selby's Treble Bid | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=27 April 2013}}</ref> In his first World Championship quarter-final he defeated [[Ding Junhui]] 13\u20137 to progress to the semi-finals, where he played [[Ricky Walden]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~3163639,00.html |title=Hawkins Stuns Ding To Reach Semis |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |accessdate=1 May 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130503182241/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0%2C%2C13165~3163639%2C00.html |archivedate=3 May 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref> Hawkins struggled for form during the first two sessions, playing some gritty snooker to trail only 6\u20138 with a high break of just 36 and received ironic cheers and a punch of the air from Hawkins when he made 47 in the next frame.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://au.eurosport.com/snooker/walden-pulls-clear-of-hawkins-in-crucible-semi_sto3739384/story.shtml | title=Gritty Hawkins pegs back Walden | publisher=[[Eurosport]] | accessdate=4 May 2013}}</ref> He went on to fall 8\u201312 behind but then began to find his game, as Walden's deteriorated, to win eight successive frames with two centuries in the process. Despite a brief fightback from Walden, Hawkins won the match 17\u201314 to set up a clash in the final with defending champion [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]], Hawkins saying he had nothing to lose now.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/22386595 | title=World Snooker Championship 2013: Hawkins beats Walden | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=4 May 2013}}</ref> Hawkins fought gallantly throughout the final making breaks of 127 and 133, his highest ever at the Crucible, but every time he applied pressure to his opponent, O'Sullivan responded with clinical scoring which included six century breaks and a further 10 breaks of 50 throughout the match as he defeated Hawkins 18\u201312.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~3169757,00.html | title=O'Sullivan Captures Fifth World Crown | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=6 May 2013}}</ref> For reaching the final he received prize money of \u00a3125,000, three times more than his previous biggest pay-day. Hawkins' turnaround from being a solid player to a ranking event winner and World Championship runner-up has been credited, in part, to his work with [[1979 World Snooker Championship|1979]] champion [[Terry Griffiths]] who has helped to give him the self-belief to make the most of his game.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~3167582,00.html | title=Hawk Lands in World Final | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=4 May 2013 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130507121407/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0%2C%2C13165~3167582%2C00.html | archivedate=7 May 2013 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> His successful season saw him climb 13 spots in the rankings to a career high world number nine, the first time he has finished a season inside the top 16 since 2006.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/49/bc/0,,13165~179273,00.pdf |title=Official World Snooker Ranking List For The 2013/2014 Season |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |accessdate=28 May 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130611202605/http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/49/bc/0%2C%2C13165~179273%2C00.pdf |archivedate=11 June 2013 |df=dmy }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.snooker.org/rnk/history.asp | title=Ranking History | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=28 May 2013}}</ref>\n\n===2013/2014===\nAfter a pair of second round exits in the opening two rankings events of the [[Snooker season 2013/2014|2013/2014 season]], Hawkins levelled his quarter-final match against [[Mark Selby]] at the [[2013 Shanghai Masters|Shanghai Masters]] with a 140 break and then won the deciding frame to progress.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/snooker/24182324 | title=Shanghai Masters: Ding Junhui beats Neil Robertson | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> In the semi-finals he was unable to match [[Ding Junhui]]'s form as he was beaten 6\u20132.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://asia.eurosport.com/snooker/shanghai-masters/2013-2014/xiao-to-face-ding-in-first-all-chinese-ranking-final_sto3932485/story.shtml | title=Xiao to face Ding in first all-Chinese ranking final | publisher=[[Eurosport]] | accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> In a deciding frame against [[Shaun Murphy (snooker player)|Shaun Murphy]], Hawkins potted seven reds and seven blacks but had to make do with a break of 70 to take the match and reach the quarter-finals of the [[2013 UK Championship (snooker)|UK Championship]] for the first in his career.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~3561322,00.html | title=Maguire And Hawkins Into Quarters | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> Hawkins led Selby 5\u20133, but went on to be beaten 6\u20135.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~3564287,00.html | title=Selby Wins Hawkins Thriller | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> In the semi-finals of the [[2014 Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]] he lost 6\u20132 against [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.espn.co.uk/snooker/sport/story/287841.html | title=O'Sullivan and Ding to meet in Welsh Open final | publisher=[[ESPN (UK)]] | accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref>\n\n====Second ranking title====\nHawkins played in all eight [[Players Tour Championship 2013/2014|European Tour]] events during the season with his best result being a semi-final defeat at the [[European Tour 2013/2014 \u2013 Event 1|Bulgarian Open]], which helped him finish 25th on the [[Players Tour Championship 2013/2014#European Tour|Order of Merit]] and claim the final spot for the [[Players Tour Championship 2013/2014 \u2013 Finals|Finals]].<ref>{{cite web|title=European Order of Merit 2013/2014|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?template=10&season=2013|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=30 April 2014|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140408124026/http://snooker.org/res/index.asp?template=10&season=2013|archivedate=8 April 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref> There he whitewashed [[Stephen Maguire]] 4\u20130 in the first round and then saw off [[Ryan Day (snooker player)|Ryan Day]] 4\u20133 in an extremely tight match.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.yourcanterbury.co.uk/sport/barry_hawkins_faces_conqueror_of_ronnie_o_sullivan_1_3494451 | title=Barry Hawkins faces conqueror of Ronnie O'Sullivan | publisher=Your Canterbury | accessdate=30 April 2014 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140502032638/http://www.yourcanterbury.co.uk/sport/barry_hawkins_faces_conqueror_of_ronnie_o_sullivan_1_3494451 | archive-date=2 May 2014 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Comfortable 4\u20131 victories over [[Yu Delu]] and [[Judd Trump]] followed as he reached the final.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=16 | title=Barry Hawkins 2013/2014 | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=30 April 2014}}</ref> He faced an unlikely opponent in world number 66 and practice partner [[Gerard Greene]]. Hawkins did not give Greene a chance as he won the first two frames without him registering a point and completed a 4\u20130 win to take the \u00a3100,000 first prize.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~3739023,00.html |title=Hawkins Storms To Players Title |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |accessdate=30 April 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140402172933/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0%2C%2C13165~3739023%2C00.html |archivedate=2 April 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\nAt the [[2014 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]], Hawkins played [[Ricky Walden]] in the second round, a repeat of last year's semi-final. The match was similar to the one 12 months earlier too, as Hawkins fought back from a 9\u20135 deficit to win 13\u201311.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/sport/hawkins-into-quarter-finals-16416/ | title=Ditton snooker player Barry Hawkins beats Ricky Walden at World Snooker Championships in Sheffield | publisher=[[KM Group|Kent Online]] | accessdate=29 April 2014}}</ref> He built an 11\u20135 lead over [[Dominic Dale]] after two sessions of their quarter-final, but upon the resumption of play Dale incredibly won seven frames in a row to stand just one away from equalling the biggest comeback in a quarter-final at the [[The Crucible|Crucible]]. However, Hawkins regrouped and made breaks of 66 and 65 to win the last two frames and move into the semi-finals, where he faced [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] in a rematch of the previous year's final. Hawkins trailed 2\u20136 after the first session and 5\u201311 after the second session, and lost the match 7\u201317 with a session to spare.<ref>{{cite news|title=Ronnie O'Sullivan beats Barry Hawkins in World Snooker semis|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/0/snooker/27246065|work=[[BBC Sport]]|accessdate=2 May 2014|date=2 May 2014}}</ref> Hawkins was the world number five at the end of the campaign, the highest he has ever finished a season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/71/c1/0,,13165~180593,00.pdf |title=World Snooker Rankings After the 2014 World Championship |publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] |accessdate=9 May 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140508030740/http://www.worldsnooker.com/staticFiles/71/c1/0%2C%2C13165~180593%2C00.pdf |archivedate=8 May 2014 |df=dmy }}</ref>\n\n===2014/2015===\nHawkins first ranking event of the [[Snooker season 2014/2015|2014/2015 season]] was the [[2014 Wuxi Classic]] and he beat [[Marco Fu]] 5\u20134 to reach the semi-finals, stating later that he was gaining more self belief due to being in the latter stages of big events more regularly.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://en.espn.co.uk/snooker/sport/story/319549.html | title=Robertson slams 'unpredictable' conditions | publisher=[[ESPN (UK)]] | accessdate=29 April 2015}}</ref> From 3\u20133, [[Neil Robertson (snooker player)|Neil Robertson]] took a trio of frames to defeat Hawkins 6\u20133.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www1.skysports.com/more-sports/snooker/news/12243/9364919/wuxi-classic-neil-robertson-and-joe-perry-into-final-of-season-opening-ranking-event | title=Wuxi Classic: Neil Robertson and Joe Perry into final of season-opening ranking event | publisher=[[Sky Sports]] | accessdate=30 April 2015}}</ref>\nHe was unable to build on his good start to the season however, as he could not advance beyond the last 32 of the next three ranking events and in the second round of the [[2014 UK Championship (snooker)|UK Championship]] he lost 6\u20135 to [[Nigel Bond]] after Hawkins had been 5\u20130 up.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/sport/hawkins-i-blew-it-27834/ | title=Barry Hawkins can't hide his frustration after blowing 5-0 lead against Nigel Bond in UK Snooker Championship | publisher=[[KM Group|Kent Online]] | accessdate=29 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2015, he achieved the second [[maximum break]] of his career in his league stage match against [[Stephen Maguire]] in group{{nbsp}}1 of the [[2015 Championship League|Championship League]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Hawkins Makes 147 At CLS|url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0,,13165~4402307,00.html|work=worldsnooker.com|publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association]]|date=6 January 2015|accessdate=6 January 2015|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150106132507/http://www.worldsnooker.com/page/NewsArticles/0%2C%2C13165~4402307%2C00.html|archivedate=6 January 2015|df=dmy-all}}</ref> His form in ranking events did not improve though as he was knocked out in the first round of the [[2015 German Masters|German Masters]] and [[Players Tour Championship 2014/2015 \u2013 Finals|PTC Grand Final]] and the second round of the [[2015 Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]].<ref name=\"2014/15\">{{cite web|title=Barry Hawkins 2014/2015|url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?season=2014&player=16|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=29 April 2015}}</ref> An improvement came at the [[2015 China Open (snooker)|China Open]] with wins over [[Gerard Greene]], [[Dominic Dale]] and [[Stephen Maguire]]. In the quarter-finals he was ousted 5\u20133 by world number 56 [[Gary Wilson (snooker player)|Gary Wilson]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/ding-to-face-wilson-in-beijing/ | title=Ding to Face Wilson in Beijing | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=30 April 2015}}</ref>\n\nHawkins looked to be cruising into the second round of the [[2015 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]] after he took the opening session of his match with [[Matthew Selt]] 7\u20132 and extended it to 9\u20134. However, Selt won five frames on the trot to take the match into a deciding frame which Hawkins won. Hawkins said afterwards that his poor form in the middle part of this season was down to him having a bad attitude due to the amount of snooker he has played in the last two years.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/othersports/article-3047473/Barry-Hawkins-books-place-World-Snooker-Championship-second-round-win-Matthew-Selt.html | title=Barry Hawkins books place in World Snooker Championship second round with win over Matthew Selt | newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] | accessdate=29 April 2015}}</ref> Hawkins produced a great comeback in the next round against [[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]] by winning five frames in a row to triumph 13\u201311 and stated that the unique atmosphere of the [[Crucible Theatre]] helps him focus harder and is the reason for his recent good form in the event.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.kentonline.co.uk/maidstone/sport/hawkins-holds-his-nerve-35815/ | title=Ditton's Barry Hawkins beats Mark Allen 13-11 to reach quarter-final of the World Snooker Championship | publisher=[[KM Group|Kent Online]] | accessdate=29 April 2015}}</ref> In the quarter-finals, Hawkins won six frames from 3\u20131 behind, restricting his opponent [[Neil Robertson (snooker player)|Neil Robertson]] to just eight points in the process.<ref name=\"2014/15\"/> The tie would eventually go into a deciding frame which Hawkins won with a 61 break to reach the semi-finals for the third year in a row. It was an extremely high quality encounter, during which both players made four centuries each to equal a World Championship record for a best of 25 frame match.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www1.skysports.com/snooker/news/12040/9828457/shaun-murphy-joins-judd-trump-in-world-championship-semi-finals | title=Shaun Murphy joins Judd Trump in World Championship semi-finals | publisher=[[Sky Sports]] | accessdate=29 April 2015}}</ref> Hawkins endured a tough semi-final as he fell 14\u20133 behind [[Shaun Murphy (snooker player)|Shaun Murphy]] and only just avoided losing with a session to spare, as he returned to be defeated 17\u20139.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.theguardian.com/sport/2015/may/02/shaun-murphy-barry-hawkins-crucible-final | title=Shaun Murphy eases past Barry Hawkins and into Crucible final | newspaper=[[The Guardian]] | accessdate=3 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n===2015/2016===\nHawkins took two months off at the beginning of the season and said he would be more selective with the events he enters in order to remain fresh for the entire year.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/hawk-ready-to-soar/ | title=Hawk Ready to Soar | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=11 August 2015}}</ref> He returned for the minor-ranking [[European Tour 2015/2016 \u2013 Event 1|Riga Open]] and won it by defeating [[Tom Ford (snooker player)|Tom Ford]] 4\u20131 in the final. Hawkins conceded only a total of seven frames in his seven matches during the event.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/hawkins-rules-in-riga/ | title=Hawkins Rules In Riga | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=11 August 2015 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150807221600/http://www.worldsnooker.com/hawkins-rules-in-riga/ | archivedate=7 August 2015 | df=dmy-all }}</ref> A series of early ranking event exits followed, but Hawkins recaptured his form at the [[2016 Masters (snooker)|Masters]].<ref name=\"2015/16\">{{cite web | url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=16&season=2015 | title=Barry Hawkins 2015/2016 | publisher=Snooker.org | accessdate=16 January 2016}}</ref> In an event where he had never won a match in five prior appearances, Hawkins eliminated [[Joe Perry (snooker player)|Joe Perry]] 6\u20133, [[Mark Allen (snooker player)|Mark Allen]] 6\u20132 and [[Judd Trump]] 6\u20134 to set up a meeting with [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]] in the final.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/othersports/article-3402726/Barry-Hawkins-reaches-Masters-final-surprise-victory-Judd-Trump.html | title=Barry Hawkins reaches first Masters final with surprise victory over Judd Trump | newspaper=[[Daily Mail]] | accessdate=16 January 2016}}</ref> Hawkins took the opening frame, but would lose 10\u20131 to equal the record of the biggest margin of defeat in a Masters final set by [[Steve Davis|Steve Davis']] 9\u20130 whitewash over [[Mike Hallett]] in [[1988 Masters (snooker)|1988]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/35338789 | title=Masters: Ronnie O'Sullivan beats Barry Hawkins to win sixth title | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=17 January 2016}}</ref> In the [[Players Tour Championship 2015/2016 \u2013 Finals|PTC Finals]], Hawkins eliminated [[Michael Holt (snooker player)|Michael Holt]] 4\u20132, [[Robert Milkins]] 4\u20133 and [[Ding Junhui]] 4\u20132.<ref name=\"2015/16\"/> He lost 6\u20133 to [[Ricky Walden]] in the semi-finals.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/walden-beats-hawkins-to-reach-final/ | title=Walden beats Hawkins to Reach Final | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=6 August 2016}}</ref>\n\nHawkins met O'Sullivan in the second round of the [[2016 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]], a player who he had not beat in 10 matches stretching back 14 years since their very first meeting. Hawkins led 9\u20137 after the second session and 12\u20139 to stand one frame away of the win. However, O'Sullivan quickly levelled the match at 12\u201312, but went in off during the deciding frame to allow Hawkins to be the only player to have reached the quarter-finals of the event for the past three years. Hawkins said the change from his heavy defeat to O'Sullivan at the Masters in January to beating him was playing the balls instead of his opponent and that he was proud of having handled the most pressure he ever felt during his career.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/snooker/36135899 | title=World Snooker Championship: Ronnie O'Sullivan loses to Barry Hawkins | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=6 August 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/snooker/36138066 | title=World Snooker Championship: Barry Hawkins relishes Ronnie O'Sullivan win | work=[[BBC Sport]] | accessdate=6 August 2016}}</ref> The match seemed to take a lot out of Hawkins as he was 9\u20131 behind [[Marco Fu]] in the quarters, but he rediscovered his form to be just 10\u20139 and 12\u201311 down. In the next frame Hawkins was 60\u20130 ahead, before Fu made a 74 break to close out the match. Afterwards Hawkins said he had not slept at all after his win over O'Sullivan and was unable to focus during the first session of the Fu match.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/fu-survives-hawkins-fight-back/ | title=Fu Survives Hawkins Fightback | publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]] | accessdate=6 August 2016}}</ref>\n\n===2016/2017===\nAfter not getting past the third round in the early part of the [[Snooker season 2016/2017|2016/2017 season]], Hawkins reached the semi-finals of the [[2016 English Open (snooker)|English Open]], where he lost 6\u20132 to [[Judd Trump]].<ref name=\"2016/17\">{{cite web | url=http://www.snooker.org/res/index.asp?player=16| title=Barry Hawkins 2016/2017| publisher=Snooker.org| accessdate=9 January 2017}}</ref> The next Home Nations event was the [[2016 Northern Ireland Open|Northern Ireland Open]] and Hawkins again won through to the semi-finals. [[Anthony Hamilton (snooker player)|Anthony Hamilton]] came back from 4\u20132 and 5\u20133 down to send the match in to a deciding frame in which he feathered the white when well placed to hand Hawkins a chance for the match which he took.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/38039801| title=Northern Ireland Open: Anthony Hamilton loses semi-final after white ball mishap| work=[[BBC Sport]]| accessdate=9 January 2017}}</ref> Hawkins was 5\u20131 ahead of [[Mark King (snooker player)|Mark King]] in the final, before King won five frames in a row. Hawkins won a re-spotted black to make it 8\u20138 and then lost the deciding frame.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/38045803| title=Northern Ireland Open: Mark King ends 25-year wait for ranking title| work=[[BBC Sport]]| accessdate=9 January 2017}}</ref> In the second round of the [[2016 UK Championship|UK Championship]], [[Fergal O'Brien]] became the first player to make five centuries in a best-of-11 frame match as he edged out Hawkins 6\u20135.<ref>{{cite news | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/five-ton-fergal-floors-hawk/| title=Five-Ton Fergal Floors Hawk| work=[[BBC Sport]]| accessdate=9 January 2017}}</ref> Hawkins had a good run at the [[2017 Masters (snooker)|Masters]], needing only one frame to reach the final for a second consecutive time. He had a 5\u20132 advantage in his semi-final match against [[Joe Perry (snooker player)|Joe Perry]], before Perry secured the snooker he needed to reduce the lead to 5\u20133. Perry went on to win the three remaining frames, clinching the match and narrowly denying Hawkins a rematch against defending champion [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/battling-perry-earns-rocket-final/| title=Battling Perry Earns Rocket Final| publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]]| accessdate=22 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nHawkins beat [[Kyren Wilson]] 4\u20132, [[Judd Trump]] 4\u20131, [[Neil Robertson (snooker player)|Neil Robertson]] 4\u20132 and [[Liang Wenbo]] 6\u20131 to reach the final of the\n[[2017 World Grand Prix|World Grand Prix]]. He made five century breaks to be 9\u20133 up on [[Ryan Day (snooker player)|Ryan Day]] who then closed the gap to 9\u20137, before Hawkins took the next frame to win his third ranking title.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/snooker/38951981| title=World Grand Prix: Barry Hawkins beats Ryan Day to win title in Preston| work=[[BBC Sport]]| accessdate=19 February 2017}}</ref>\n\nHe lost 5\u20134 on the final black to Trump in the quarter-finals of the [[2017 Welsh Open (snooker)|Welsh Open]].<ref name=\"2016/17\"/> Victories over [[Tom Ford (snooker player)|Tom Ford]], [[Graeme Dott]] and [[Stephen Maguire]] saw Hawkins play in his fourth [[2017 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]] semi-final in five years, but he didn't capatalise on the chances that came his way against [[John Higgins (snooker player)|John Higgins]] and was eliminated 17\u20138.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.worldsnooker.com/higgins-reaches-sixth-world-final/| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170508203654/http://www.worldsnooker.com/higgins-reaches-sixth-world-final/| url-status=dead| archive-date=8 May 2017| title=Higgins Reaches Sixth World Final| publisher=[[World Professional Billiards and Snooker Association|World Snooker]]| accessdate=29 April 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Technique==\nHawkins is naturally right-handed but plays with his cue left-handed. However, if he has to use the rest, he switches the [[Cue stick|cue]] to his dominant hand (right hand) for better handling. Additionally, it allows him to aim better because his right eye is his objective eye.{{citation needed|date=April 2016}}\n<gallery>\nBarry Hawkins at Snooker German Masters (DerHexer) 2013-01-30 2.jpg|Hawkins holding the cue stick in his left hand for a regular shot\nBarry Hawkins at Snooker German Masters (DerHexer) 2013-02-02 15.jpg|Hawkins holds a rest in his left hand{{nbsp}}...\nBarry Hawkins at Snooker German Masters (DerHexer) 2013-01-30 6.jpg|...{{nbsp}}and the cue in his right.\n</gallery>\n\n==Personal life==\nHawkins has been with his partner Tara since 2001; in January 2009 they had their first child, a son named Harrison,<ref name=\"Legend Davis through to Crucible\" /> and they were married in June 2012.<ref name=\"Aus\"/>\n\n==Performance and rankings timeline==\n<div style=\"width:auto; overflow:scroll\">\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:85%;\"\n|- style=\"background:#efefef;\"\n! '''Tournament'''\n! [[Snooker season 1996/1997|1996/<br/>97]]\n! [[Snooker season 1997/1998|1997/<br/>98]]\n! [[Snooker season 1998/1999|1998/<br/>99]]\n! [[Snooker season 1999/2000|1999/<br/>00]]\n! [[Snooker season 2000/2001|2000/<br/>01]]\n! [[Snooker season 2001/2002|2001/<br/>02]]\n! [[Snooker season 2002/2003|2002/<br/>03]]\n! [[Snooker season 2003/2004|2003/<br/>04]]\n! [[Snooker season 2004/2005|2004/<br/>05]]\n! [[Snooker season 2005/2006|2005/<br/>06]]\n! [[Snooker season 2006/2007|2006/<br/>07]]\n! [[Snooker season 2007/2008|2007/<br/>08]]\n! [[Snooker season 2008/2009|2008/<br/>09]]\n! [[Snooker season 2009/2010|2009/<br/>10]]\n! [[Snooker season 2010/2011|2010/<br/>11]]\n! [[Snooker season 2011/2012|2011/<br/>12]]\n! [[Snooker season 2012/2013|2012/<br/>13]]\n! [[Snooker season 2013/2014|2013/<br/>14]]\n! [[Snooker season 2014/2015|2014/<br/>15]]\n! [[Snooker season 2015/2016|2015/<br/>16]]\n! [[Snooker season 2016/2017|2016/<br/>17]]\n! [[Snooker season 2017/2018|2017/<br/>18]]\n! [[Snooker season 2018/2019|2018/<br/>19]]\n! [[2019\u201320 snooker season|2019/<br/>20]]\n|-\n| style=\"background:#EFEFEF;\" | [[Snooker world rankings|Ranking]]<ref name=\"Ranking history\">{{cite web|title=Ranking History|url=http://www.snooker.org/rnk/history.asp|publisher=Snooker.org|accessdate=6 February 2011}}</ref><ref group=\"nb\">From the 2010/2011 season it shows the ranking at the beginning of the season.</ref> \n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref group=\"nb\" name=\"UR\">New players on the Main Tour don't have a ranking.</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref group=\"nb\" name=\"AMA\">He was an amateur.</ref>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref group=\"nb\" name=\"AMA\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref group=\"nb\" name=\"AMA\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|<ref group=\"nb\" name=\"UR\"/>\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Snooker world rankings 2001/2002|85]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Snooker world rankings 2002/2003|51]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Snooker world rankings 2003/2004|42]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Snooker world rankings 2004/2005|43]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Snooker world rankings 2005/2006|30]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Snooker world rankings 2006/2007|12]]\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"|[[Snooker world rankings 2007/2008|19]]\n| style=\"text-align:cent