agicon|ENG}} [[Craig Butler (snooker player)|Craig Butler]]\n| align=\"center\"|6\u20131\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"ffa07a\"|Runner-up\n| 3.\n| [[2007 Irish Masters|2007]]\n| [[Irish Masters|Kilkenny Irish Masters]]\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]]\n| align=\"center\"|1\u20139\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"98FB98\"|Winner\n| 2.\n| [[2008 Masters (snooker)#Qualifying|2007]]\n| [[Masters Qualifying Event]]\n| {{flagicon|NOR}} [[Kurt Maflin]]\n| align=\"center\"|6\u20134\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"ffa07a\"|Runner-up\n| 4.\n| 2008\n| Hamm Invitational\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]]\n| align=\"center\"|2\u22126\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"98FB98\"|Winner\n| 3.\n| 2010\n| [[Pro Challenge Series 2009/2010 \u2013 Event 5|Pro Challenge Series \u2013 Event 5]]\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Michael Holt (snooker player)|Michael Holt]]\n| align=\"center\"|5\u20131\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"98FB98\"|Winner\n| 4.\n| [[2012 Snooker Shoot-Out|2012]]\n| [[Snooker Shoot Out]]\n| {{flagicon|SCO}} [[Graeme Dott]]\n| align=\"center\"|1\u20130\n|-\n|- style=\"background:#ffc;\"\n| bgcolor=\"ffa07a\"|Runner-up\n| 5.\n| [[2016 Masters (snooker)|2016]]\n| [[Masters (snooker)|The Masters]]\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]]\n| align=\"center\"|1\u201310\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"ffa07a\"|Runner-up\n| 6.\n| [[2018 Shanghai Masters|2018]]\n| [[Shanghai Masters (snooker)|Shanghai Masters]]\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]]\n| align=\"center\"|9\u201311\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"98FB98\"|Winner\n| 5.\n| [[2019 Paul Hunter Classic|2019]]\n| [[Paul Hunter Classic]]\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} [[Kyren Wilson]]\n| align=\"center\"|4\u20133\n|}\n\n===Variant finals: 2 (1 title, 1 runner-up)===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|width=\"80\"|'''Outcome'''\n|width=\"20\"|'''No.'''\n|width=\"50\"|'''Year'''\n|style=\"width:250px;\"|'''Championship'''\n|style=\"width:200px;\"|'''Opponent in the final'''\n|style=\"text-align:center; width:50px;\"|'''Score'''\n|-\n| bgcolor=\"ffa07a\"|Runner-up\n| 1.\n| [[2009 Six-red World Grand Prix|2009]]\n| [[Six-red World Grand Prix]]\n| {{flagicon|ENG}} {{sortname|Jimmy|White}}\n| align=\"center\"|6\u20138\n|-\n|style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Winner\n| 1.\n| [[2018 Macau Masters|2018]]\n| [[2018 Macau Masters|Six-red Macau Masters]]\n| {{flagicon|WAL}} [[Mark Williams (snooker player)|Mark Williams]]\n| align=\"center\"|3\u20132\n|}\n\n===Team finals: 2 (1 title, 1 runner-up)===\n{| class=\"sortable wikitable\"\n|width=\"80\"|'''Outcome'''\n|width=\"20\"|'''No.'''\n|width=\"50\"|'''Year'''\n|width=\"150\"|'''Championship'''\n|width=\"100\"|'''Team'''/'''Partner'''\n|width=\"100\"|'''{{nowrap|Opponent(s) in the final}}'''\n|width=\"50\"|'''Score'''\n|-\n| style=\"background:#ffa07a;\"|Runner-up\n| 1.\n| [[2017 World Cup (snooker)|2017]]\n| [[World Cup (snooker)|World Cup]]\n| {{flagcountry|ENG}}\n| {{flagcountry|CHN}} A\n| align=\"center\" | 3\u20134\n|-\n| style=\"background:#98fb98;\"|Winner \n| 1.\n| 2018\n| [[2018 Macau Masters|Macau Masters]]\n| {{flagicon|WAL}} [[Ryan Day (snooker player)|Ryan Day]]<br />{{flagicon|CHN}} [[Zhao Xintong]]<br />{{flagicon|CHN}} [[Zhou Yuelong]]\n| {{flagicon|WAL}} [[Mark Williams (snooker player)|Mark Williams]]<br />{{flagicon|ENG}} [[Joe Perry (snooker player)|Joe Perry]]<br />{{flagicon|HKG}} [[Marco Fu]]<br />{{flagicon|CHN}} [[Zhang Anda]]\n| align=\"center\" | 5\u20131\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Barry Hawkins}}\n*{{Official website|1=http://onqpromotions.co.uk/players/BarryHawkins.html}}\n*[http://www.worldsnooker.com/players/barry-hawkins/ Barry Hawkins] at ''worldsnooker.com''\n*\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090913063729/http://www.global-snooker.com/Barry-Hawkins.asp Profile at Global Snooker]\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2013}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Hawkins, Barry}}\n[[Category:English snooker players]]\n[[Category:1979 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Dartford]]\n", "name_user": "Lee Vilenski", "label": "safe", "comment": "cleanup - fix season links usingWP:AWB", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Barry_Hawkins"}
{"title_page": "Dave Harold", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=April 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2015}}\n{{Infobox snooker player\n| name          = Dave Harold\n| image         = Dave Harold PHC 2012-3.jpg\n| caption       = Paul Hunter Classic 2012\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1966|12|9}} \n| birth_place   = {{smaller|[[Stoke-on-Trent]], [[Staffordshire]], [[England]]}} \n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| Sport country = {{ENG}}\n| Nickname      = The [[Stoke-on-Trent|Stoke]] {{Cuegloss|Pot|Potter}} \n| Professional  = 1991\u20132015\n| High ranking  = 11 {{smaller|([[Snooker world rankings 1996/1997|1996/1997]])}} \n| Prize money   = [[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]1,094,982\n| High break    = '''143''': <br />{{smaller|2007 Grand Prix}} \n| Century break = 143\n| Ranking wins  = 1\n| Other wins    = 1\n| World champ   = \n}}\n\n'''David \"Dave\" Harold''' (born 9 December 1966) is an English former professional [[snooker]] player from [[Stoke-on-Trent]]. He was known by the nicknames of \"the Hard Man\" and \"the Stoke Potter\" (conflating his home city's [[pottery]] industry and his profession of potting snooker balls). He was also the first player on the television circuit to sport a plaster on his chin as a guide for his cue,{{citation needed|date=December 2013}} which is a practice now adopted by Graeme Dott. As an amateur he played as David Harold, but since turning professional in 1991 he was registered as Dave Harold. He has three children and is separated from his wife.<ref>http://www.worldsnooker.com/news_editorial-19475.htm{{full citation needed|date=December 2013}}</ref>\n \nHe won one ranking title, reached two further finals and several semi-finals, and spent four seasons ranked among the top 16. Harold was renowned for both his very strong defensive play and his unusual cue-action, with which he is able to unleash a great deal of power on a shot without using backswing on the cue.{{citation needed|date=December 2013}} Despite safety play ultimately being considered his strong point, he compiled 143 century breaks, putting him 22nd on the all-time list.<ref name=\"Chris Turners TOP CENTURY MAKERS\">{{Cite web\n| url = http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/Centuries.htm|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130210111241/http://www.cajt.pwp.blueyonder.co.uk/Centuries.htm|archivedate=10 February 2013 \n| title = Chris Turner's Snooker Archive \u2013 Top Century Makers\n| publisher =\n| year = 2008\n| accessdate = 30 August 2008\n}}</ref> [[Steve Davis]] has commented that he is not the most naturally gifted player, but makes up for this with strong tactical play.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/world_champs_2002/player_profiles/1919235.stm | work=BBC News | title=15. Dave Harold | date=11 April 2002 | accessdate=1 May 2010}}</ref> For his technique and grinding play he has been compared to [[Cliff Thorburn]].\n\n==Career==\n\n===Early career===\n\nSoon after turning professional, Harold won the [[1993 Asian Open]], beating [[Darren Morgan]] 9\u20133 in the final. Ranked 93rd in the world at the time, he became the lowest-ranked player ever to win a ranking tournament.{{citation needed|date=December 2013}} He never repeated this achievement, although he reached his second ranking final in the 1994 [[Grand Prix (snooker)|Grand Prix]], losing 6\u20139 to [[John Higgins (snooker player)|John Higgins]].\n\n===Top 16 (1996\u20132002)===\n\nAfter 1994 Harold did not reach a third ranking final until 2008, although he has career reached a total of ten semi-finals in ranking tournaments to date, and was a Top-16 player for four seasons between [[Snooker world rankings 1995/1996|1995/1996]] and [[Snooker world rankings 2001/2002|2001/2002]], reaching a career-best position of no. 11 in the [[Snooker world rankings 1996/1997|world rankings in the 1996/97 season]]. In the 1996 Welsh Open, he lost in the semi-finals, 1\u20136, to eventual winner [[Mark Williams (snooker player)|Mark Williams]].\n\nHe contended in his first and only [[World Snooker Championship|World Championship]] quarter-final in [[World Snooker Championship 1996|the 1996 event]], where he lost 7\u201313 to [[Nigel Bond]]. He also lost 5\u20136 to Bond in his 1996 British Open semi-final less than two weeks earlier.\n\nIn the 1998 [[Grand Prix (snooker)|Grand Prix]], he knocked out [[Stephen Hendry]] and [[John Higgins (snooker player)|John Higgins]] en route to the semi-finals, but lost narrowly to eventual champion [[Stephen Lee (snooker player)|Stephen Lee]]. 1998 also saw him reach his first semi-final in the UK Championship, where he was defeated 9\u20137 by [[Matthew Stevens]].\n\nIn the 1999 [[Grand Prix (snooker)|Grand Prix]] Harold led Mark Williams 5\u20133 in the semi-finals but lost 5\u20136. This was Harold's last ranking semi-final until 2008, although he also reached the semis in the non-ranking 2001 [[Masters (snooker)|Masters]], defeating [[John Higgins (snooker player)|John Higgins]] and [[John Parrott]], but losing his semi-final 5\u20136 to eventual runner-up [[Fergal O'Brien]] after having led 5\u20131.\n\n===2003\u20132015===\nFollowing a poor season in 2001\u20132002, Harold dropped out of the Top 16, down to number 29 in the World Rankings. A broken wrist sustained on New Year's Eve 2003 saw him drop further down the rankings,{{citation needed|date=December 2013}} out of the top 32, although he had a better [[Snooker world rankings 2005/2006|2005/2006 season]]. Another consistent season in [[Snooker world rankings 2006/2007|2006/2007]] helped Harold back up to No. 30 in the [[Snooker world rankings 2007/2008|world rankings for 2007/2008]].\n\n2007/2008 started with a quarter-final appearance in the [[Shanghai Masters (snooker)|Shanghai Masters]], losing to eventual winner [[Dominic Dale]]. Harold did not get past the round robin phase of the [[Grand Prix (snooker)|Grand Prix]], finishing fifth in his group of six players; but in the 2007 [[UK Championship]], Harold eliminated World Number 2 [[Graeme Dott]] 9\u20137 in the first round to achieve a place in the last 16 of the tournament for the first time since 1999. However, he lost 2\u20139 in the second round to [[Mark Selby]]. He qualified for the final stages of the World Championship with a 10\u20134 win over [[Mike Dunn (snooker player)|Mike Dunn]], but lost 10\u20133 at the Crucible in the first round proper to [[Shaun Murphy (snooker player)|Shaun Murphy]].\n\nDuring a preliminary round match against local wildcard [[Jin Long (snooker player)|Jin Long]] in the [[China Open 2008 (snooker)|2008 China Open]], Harold was locked at 4\u20134. He took time out before the deciding frame to leave the playing arena and consume a couple of bananas, returning replenished to finish the job with a clearance on the colours. This gave rise to the affectionate nickname \"[[Bananaman]]\" on the [[Betfair]] snooker forum,{{citation needed|date=December 2013}} referring to a children's TV character who gained superhuman powers. Harold also put up a battle against [[Shaun Murphy (snooker player)|Shaun Murphy]] in the next round, but eventually lost 5\u20133; the last frame set a record at the time for being the longest ever in snooker history (93 minutes and 12 seconds).{{citation needed|date=December 2013}}\n\nHarold retained his Top 32 ranking, and started the [[2008\u201309 snooker season|2008\u201309]] season ranked at [[Snooker world rankings 2008/2009|#28]], his highest ranking since 2003. In the first ranking event of the new season, the [[2008 Northern Ireland Trophy]], he beat [[Ricky Walden]] 5\u20132, [[Graeme Dott]] 5\u20133, [[Stephen Lee (snooker player)|Stephen Lee]] 5\u20134 and defending champion [[Stephen Maguire]] to reach the semi-finals, his first appearance at that stage of a ranking event for five years. He then moved into a 5\u20131 lead against [[John Higgins (snooker player)|John Higgins]] and won 6\u20134, to reach his first final since 1994, which he lost 9\u20133 to [[Ronnie O'Sullivan]].<ref>\"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/other_sports/snooker/7591068.stm Classy O'Sullivan wins NI Trophy]\", BBC Sport, 31 August 2008. Retrieved on 1 September 2008.</ref> Harold's performance in this tournament moved him up to 14th in the provisional world rankings. Harold remarked after the final that, aside from claiming the World Championship, his one other remaining ambition in the game is to score a victory over O'Sullivan, who he has never beaten in a ranking tournament. The [[2008 Northern Ireland Trophy]] marked his tenth consecutive failure to do so.<ref>http://www.bbc.co.uk/stoke/content/articles/2006/04/19/local_tv_archive_snooker_champs_dave_harold_ronnie_osullivan_feature.shtml</ref>\n\nHarold subsequently qualified for the [[2008 Shanghai Masters]] and [[Grand Prix (snooker)|Grand Prix]]. In the former, he defeated home favourite [[Ding Junhui]] in the last 32, before losing 4\u20135 (from 3\u20130 and 4\u20131 up) against [[Steve Davis]]; however, in the latter he was eliminated in the first round by [[Ali Carter]]. A less successful run of results in the second half of the season saw him fall out of the Top 16 in the provisional rankings, largely due to his failure to qualify for the 2009 World Championship, although he started the 2009/2010 season ranked at No. 19, an improvement of nine places on the previous season.\n\nHarold appeared in the Welsh Open in January 2010 but lost in the first round 5\u20131 to Stephen Hendry. In September he beat Shaun Murphy 3\u20130 in the newly formed World Open in Glasgow but subsequently lost in the next round to Jamie Cope 3\u20132.\n\n[[File:Dave Harold at Snooker German Masters (DerHexer) 2013-01-31 02.jpg|thumb|Dave Harold at [[2013 German Masters]].]]\nThe [[2012\u201313 snooker season|2012\u201313]] season saw Harold win 2 qualifying matches to reach the main stages of the [[2012 Wuxi Classic]], however, he lost his wildcard match to Chinese player [[Rouzi Maimaiti]]. Harold subsequently failed to qualify for the next four ranking events, losing to players such as [[Ali Carter]], [[Barry Hawkins]], and [[Cao Yupeng]]. He did, however, qualify for the [[2013 German Masters|German Masters]], beating [[Craig Steadman]] 5\u20133 and [[Ryan Day (snooker player)|Ryan Day]] 5\u20134 to qualify for the Last 32 of the event, where he lost 3\u20135 to former world champion [[Graeme Dott]]. He only won 1 more match in ranking event qualifiers for the rest of the season, culminating with a 9\u201310 defeat the [[Alfie Burden]] in qualifying for the [[2013 World Snooker Championship|World Championship]]. Harold played in many of the [[Players Tour Championship 2012/2013|Players Tour Championship]] event throughout the season, his best results being three Last 16 appearances, and a further two Last 32 results, finishing 39th on the Order of Merit, outside of the Top 26 that qualified for the [[Players Tour Championship 2012/2013 \u2013 Finals|Finals]].\n\nHarold started the [[2013\u201314 snooker season|2013\u201314]] season ranked 50th in the [[Snooker world rankings 2013/2014|world rankings]]. He retired in May 2015 after suffering from eyesight problems.<ref>{{cite news|title=Dave Harold quits snooker due to poor sight|url=http://www.stokesentinel.co.uk/Dave-Harold-quits-snooker-poor-sight/story-26434893-detail/story.html|accessdate=3 May 2015|work=[[The Sentinel (Staffordshire)|The Sentinel]]|date=3 May 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\nHarold was born in [[Stoke-on-Trent]] and still lives there to this day. He is a [[Stoke City FC]] fan.\n\n==Performance and rankings timeline==\n<div style=\"width:auto; overflow:scroll\">\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:0 1em 0 0; border:1px #aaa solid; border-collapse:collapse; font-size:85%\"\n|-\n! Tournament \n! [[1990\u201391 snooker season|1990/<br/>91]]\n! [[1991\u201392 snooker season|1991/<br/>92]]\n! [[1992\u201393 snooker season|1992/<br/>93]]\n! [[1993\u201